		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://androwis.com/blog/?p=265</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Health Insurance.  In theory it&#8217;s a pretty efficient way to finance an industry&#8230; in theory. Yet, its crippling weakpoint is partly a result of the &#8230;]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Health Insurance.  In theory it&#8217;s a pretty efficient way to finance an industry&#8230; <em>in theory</em>. Yet, its crippling weakpoint is partly a result of the many types of insurance available to consumers these days.  For instance, there&#8217;s Managed Care, Fee-for-Service (the typical type with keywords: premiums, out-of-pocket expenses, co-insurance, caps), Health Maintenance Organization, Point-of-Service, Preferred Provider Organizations, blah blah blah&#8230;  From there, your head is thrust into a spinning frenzy with the likes of Health Savings Account (HSA) and other derivatives.  Oh, and there&#8217;s Medicaid, Medicare, VA stuff, each with there own sub-insurances.  Crossing the border introduces the likes of social healthcare&#8230; etc etc etc.  Are you keeping up?</p>
<p>Probably, it&#8217;s not really that hard of a concept, nor that difficult to set up.  The majority of employed Americans are on a set-it-and-forget-it configuration where they read the fine print with their HR rep during the hiring phase, choose a plan, and then not worry about it.  During my interview &amp; hiring phases I had to do the same. Being both new to the job market and personal finance, everything was all new to me.  I had no clue  what the types, benefits (both medically or tax-wise) or logistics of each were&#8230; It was all just a blur.  As is how they and the hospital&#8217;s billing department interact.  But, what I think is happening is that a huge informational gap is feeding the industry (which in turn hikes profits for both institutions, provides theoretically unnecessary jobs, ultimately complicating the system more than need be [a topic to be addressed later]) but ultimately doing a good job to jack up prices.</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s why I think it&#8217;s bogus.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Food for thought: The Grand Debate/Debacle : Nationalized vs. Market Driven Health Care.</strong></p>
<p>We&#8217;ve all heard this before and I&#8217;m sure we&#8217;ve all taken a part of the debate:</p>
<blockquote><p>Most industrialized nations have nationalized health care (or some variant).  Why then should the US not?</p></blockquote>
<p>And then there&#8217;s the retort:</p>
<blockquote><p>Leave the market to work.  Its forces will generate the right self-sufficient system with the proper incentives.</p></blockquote>
<p>Some opinions on the topic: <a href="http://business.theatlantic.com/2009/07/a_long_long_post_about_my_reasons_for_opposing_national_health_care.php" target="_blank">Megan McAcrdle</a>,<a href="http://www.pnhp.org/" target="_blank">Physicans for a National Healthcare Program</a> , <a href="http://www.healthcare-now.org/" target="_self">Healthcare-NOW</a>; a blog discussing it more than you could care for:<a href="http://insureblog.blogspot.com/" target="_blank"> Insureblog</a>: and some news: <a href="http://voices.washingtonpost.com/health-care-reform/" target="_blank">The Washington Post</a> and <a href="http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=91972152" target="_blank">NPR&#8217;s series on health care across the world</a>.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Diving In: The Underlying Economics of the Game.</strong></p>
<p>Here&#8217;s how I see the system.  It&#8217;s two parts: one part game, one part service.</p>
<p><strong>The gam</strong><strong>e  (Private Sector), </strong>like all the casinos in Las Vegas, health insurance is setup to be extremely detail oriented with a focus on profit for the industry while risk management for the player.  But we all know how insurance works in the consumer market.  You choose a plan, agree with the terms, and pay the fees, however exorbitant.</p>
<p>-The problems I see with the private sector are hidden within the numbers.</p>
<ul>
<li>Exactly how much profit are these companies racking in from premiums?</li>
<li>What percentage of the bills are they really assuming?</li>
<li>What percentage of said bills are a direct cause of private insurance&#8217;s bureaucracy?</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>The service</strong> <strong>(Public Sector)</strong>, like your typical overworked and understaffed restaurant, the Government&#8217;s implementation of health-care provisions leaves much to be demanded.  Sure the amount of work put out by the few is to be commended, but it could be better.  Like most government programs, a restructuring is overdue, but not a complete overhaul.</p>
<ul>
<li>All of my experiences I&#8217;ve had with Medicaid have been timely and for that I commend them.</li>
<li>The inefficiencies and convolutions can&#8217;t be justified.  (Definition of disability, the provision of health-care to illegals over citizens)</li>
<li>The gap of the population the government doesn&#8217;t protect needs to be ameliorated.</li>
</ul>
<p>As I started writing this, I hadn&#8217;t a clue how I wanted to tackle the issues.  Even in the midst, I realized there&#8217;s really no way a single opinion can change the industry, but what can happen is information can be given to the small group of people caught in the midst of the financial nightmare the health industry can cause.</p>
<ol>
<li>The first thing you should do is call your insurance agent and shop around asking for catastrophic insurance and the differences between that and whatever you&#8217;re currently on.   This would have saved me quite a bit.  (Essentially, it only covers ER visits and anything stemming from that, protecting against the unforesen).</li>
<li>If you have any bills from any Dr&#8217;s offices or hospitals, don&#8217;t use services that promise to reduce your bill&#8230; you can do it for free.</li>
<li>Reduce your bills.  Go to both the hospital and Dr&#8217;s offices and plea your case.  Tell them you want to pay the bills but can&#8217;t.  Just walk in and ask.  I had a 1500 bill reduced to 450 and my hospital bill reduced by half and allowed to finance the remaining balance [Little known fact, but the insurance agencies will only pay a fraction of the bill's sticker price, which I think is messed up knowing that the medical industry is charging the people that can't pay that much the full price].</li>
<li>When you need medical care, try other avenues when you can (free clinics).</li>
</ol>
<p>So, this is more of a rant than anything really constructive (and not really a very well structured rant at that).  But the angst has built up since my bout with the hospital.  The real reason being that the steps involved in resolving emergency crises both financially and medically are baffling and backwards.  No wonder Washington isn&#8217;t able to agree on any health-care reform.  To me, trying to reform this type of system is like trying to resurrect a fickle and dying horse with only a loaded shotgun in hand; poke all you want but that puppy isn&#8217;t coming back (you should try it some time if you don&#8217;t believe me).  It seems that the medical industry is rampant with inefficiencies driven by the private insurance sector, and that the private insurance sector is raking in inordinate amounts of money, that there are real injustices with public health-care, all screwing the uninsured population.<br />
<strong>Thought for food&#8230;</strong></p>
<p>In, what I think, is the most astute and succinct argument against national health care:</p>
<blockquote><p>In a nutshell, I hate the poor and want them to die so that all my rich friends can use their bodies as mulch for their diamond ranches.  ~ Megan McArdle</p></blockquote>
<p>But in all seriousness, this industry is simply dizzying&#8230; something should be done to make it just work for everyone.  Please.</p>
<p>[photo by <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/wolfsavard/3076553972/" target="_blank">wolfsavard</a>]</p>
