		<item>
		<title>[TLoaG...] on Healthcare: the Government (part 1)</title>
		<link>http://androw.is/blog/on-healthcare-the-government</link>
		<comments>http://androw.is/blog/on-healthcare-the-government#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 15 Jan 2010 20:15:35 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Andrew AbuMoussa</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Rants]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[The Life of a Graduate]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[cost]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[government]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[graduate]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[healthcare]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[life]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[medicine]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[money]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[reform]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[stress]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://androwis.com/blog/?p=140</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[The federal legalese used to define "disabled" is such to leave one wondering if there truly exists such a person on earth (clearly I wouldn't qualify). [...It also] seems to be the state's goal and intent to punish the actual working and educated class in its constituency...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Here&#8217;s the situation:<br />
  I&#8217;m a recent grad (May &#8216;09) in limbo for entering PhD or MD/PhD program (Aug &#8216;10).  Can&#8217;t find a job as a software engineer in the mean-time (held one as a waiter with no benefits).  Went to the ER for what I thought was appendicitis and now, I&#8217;m in $4500 debt because I couldn&#8217;t afford the $500/mo COBRA extension on my parent&#8217;s insurance.  </p>
<p>Yesterday, I went to apply for emergency medicaid to cover my bills.  After about an hour of begging, learning, and discussing with a social worker there was a part on my paperwork that stated that <em>&#8220;You have the right to apply for Medicaid, but you chose not to because:&#8221;</em> and this is what I put:</p>
<blockquote><p>The federal legalese used to define &#8220;disabled&#8221; is such to leave one wondering if there truly exists such a person on earth (clearly I wouldn&#8217;t qualify).  Secondly because it seems to be the state&#8217;s goal and intent to punish the actual working and educated class in its constituency.  Very disappointed with the politicians.</p></blockquote>
<p>Before we discuss what the government should do, let&#8217;s create a rough flow chart for what happens when you enter any sort of medical care or facility.</p>
<p>1) Paper work&#8230; that&#8217;s usually a pretty memorable and recurring occasion.</p>
<p>2) The entourage&#8230; that&#8217;s what I call the army of nurses, MAs, RNs,(really anybody with a 2-3 letter abbreviation that&#8217;s not Dr.) all doing the monotonous work&#8230; which is fine b/c the Dr&#8217;s time is better spent doing the hard stuff.</p>
<p>3) See Dr. and get advice/diagnosis/etc</p>
<p>4) Pay.  This part can be pretty painless or more painful than the cause for the initial visit.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s a subtle point.  But, by enumerating the usual activities of a visit one realizes that the basic goal of a visit has been elaborated into a much more <del datetime="2010-01-16T18:38:48+00:00">artistic</del> lucrative performance.  Partly necessitated by the government and part by the industry (can you guess which is which?).  It&#8217;s pretty outstanding that out of the four events, one is much more complicated than necessary while one has been exaggerated to an excessive means (paper and paying being the two perpetrating events). What is more interesting than this transformation and magnification is the fact that both private industry and big government are responsible for the maladies in events 1 and 4.  Let&#8217;s discuss how to fix this&#8230;</p>
<p><strong>So, how and why should the government impose change to help the fraction of 47 million Americans without coverage since the system seems to be working just fine?</strong></p>
<p>Stick with me.  I know we were just discussing the paperwork and a vague financial problem but here&#8217;s the deal.  Any change at this point would be a good change for everyone involved; the American people, health care providers, but most importantly, the government.  I&#8217;m not talking about the &#8220;major government overhaul&#8221; being discussed in DC, the market doesn&#8217;t need to be corrected that much. In fact, I feel like that language is superfluous legalese coined by insurance lobbyists that in all honesty would cost us more in the long run (debatable, but not relevant to my point).  Instead what the government should be focusing on are the shortcomings and the inefficiencies it produces, not on regulating an industry.  Here&#8217;s the nitty-gritty in a few sentences:</p>
<p><strong> Implementations</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The federal government pretty much only trickles down money with regulations attached forcing states to comply with federal rules while providing some sort of health care.  That&#8217;s fine&#8230;<strong><em>BUT, potential for positive change</em></strong>
<ul>
<li>For example, the official definition for &#8220;disabled&#8221; is a federally coined definition that is imposed by the land&#8217;s courts.  Your usual arbitrary legalise.</li>
<p><br/>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Next, the dispersion of health care funding states receive (at least in North Carolina) seem to have some, quite frankly, ****ed up convolutions&#8230; <strong>PROBLEM HERE</strong>
<ul>
<li> &#8230;illegal immigrants get emergency medicaid in NC but an uninsured male between 20-59 is out of luck.</li>
<p><br/>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Continuing&#8230; there are some rather severe resource squandering programs in effect with no incentives to change&#8230;<strong>PROBLEM HERE</strong>
<ul>
<li> &#8230;medicaid in NC provides every recipient with the right to transportation to any and every &#8220;health&#8221; related appointment, which is fine in theory.  In practice, it means that a taxi will be sent to the recipient, take them to their appointment, and wait.  There&#8217;s no incentive for social workers to schedule multiple pickups or pool recipients.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Now, let&#8217;s take a step back.  In this short discussion,we&#8217;ve seen the inefficiencies in a doctor&#8217;s visit while shown some areas for possible improvement without qualifying them with numbers.  In June of 2009 the Federation for American Immigration Reform, says illegal immigrants cost the state of NC $209 million-plus in health care costs (FAIR says North Carolinians who have medical insurance also pay higher medical insurance bills to help cover the costs of those without insurance).  <a href="http://74.125.47.132/search?q=cache:239wy1opwSAJ:www.pnhp.org/+healthcare+dollar&amp;cd=1&amp;hl=en&amp;ct=clnk&amp;gl=us&amp;client=firefox-a" target="_blank">Physicians for a National Health Program</a> claims 31 cents on the dollar that is spent on health care accounts for paper work and insurance bureaucracies alone (the PNHP goes on to claim that a streamlined non-profit government run agency would save enough to pay for universal health care, but I doubt that&#8217;s  all that needs to happen, pretty skeptical in fact).  Those are pretty crazy figures, yet are still the tip of the iceberg to topics such as illegal immigrant reform and insurance regulation. [<a href="http://obsthisland.blogspot.com/2009/06/cost-of-illegal-immigration-to-north.html" target="_blank">Read more from this guy who is obviously more passionate about it than me... author of This Land.</a>]</p>
<p>In sum, what I&#8217;d like to see is for the government to get it&#8217;s head on straight and face the simpler problems at hand by dealing with the inefficiencies and injustices in the system.  All I ask:</p>
<p>1) State governments should assure coverage to all of the legal citizens before extending care to illegals.<br />
     I don&#8217;t think it&#8217;s right for me to go to the Department of Social Services and have my health care coverage for an emergency denied solely because I don&#8217;t have a child, I&#8217;m not disabled, and not an illegal immigrant.  Hopefully my thoughts on this can bring down the giant curtain naturally put up by the bureaucracy that is our government because it just doesn&#8217;t seem right.  The current implementation seems to reward poor life choices and provides incentives for laziness.</p>
<p>2) A person&#8217;s degree of &#8220;disability&#8221; should be deemed by physicians, not lawyers, judges, and politicians.<br />
   The Adult Medicaid Manual MA-2525 defines <em>disability</em>: the inability to engage in any substantial gainful activity by reason of any medically determinable physical or mental impairment or combination of impairments that is expected to result in death or which has lasted or is expected to last for a continuous period of not less than 12 months.  ????</p>
<p>3) The government assumes some responsibility and deals with the severe inefficiencies in it&#8217;s implementation of projects.<br />
    I know the medicare/medicaid transport well because I volunteered and wrote code for our local branch.  The DSS has 3 full-time members answering phones for this cause alone.  I feel like funds freed up from these and other inefficiencies could be used to pay for my emergency care.</p>
<p>4) Provide those uninsured with *at least* emergency care.<br />
    I don&#8217;t even see a dentist and I&#8217;ve had the same pair of glasses for 3 years.  I&#8217;m not asking for much, just basic life support.  Oh, and when you do get your act together, help those out who were screwed in the past.  That&#8217;s the least you can do. </p>
<p>Oh, and if that wasn&#8217;t enough, wrap your head around this, no words necessary:</p>
<p><a href="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/health-care-flow-chart-republicans-2009.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-165" title="health-care-flow-chart-republicans-2009" src="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/health-care-flow-chart-republicans-2009-1024x789.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="616" /></a></p>
<p>[photo by <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/itzafineday/2819960020/in/photostream/" target="_blank">ItzaFineDay</a>]</p>
]]></content:encoded>
