		<item>
		<title>[TLoaG...] on Healthcare (part 0)</title>
		<link>http://androw.is/blog/on-healthcare</link>
		<comments>http://androw.is/blog/on-healthcare#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 12 Jan 2010 21:35:28 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Andrew AbuMoussa</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Rants]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[The Life of a Graduate]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[finance]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[graduate]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[healthcare]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[life]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[medicaid]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[politics]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[stress]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://androwis.com/blog/?p=115</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[The first in a series exploring the sores of healthcare:  As the son of two physicians, I thought I had seen medicine from every single vantage point..]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote><p>During those trying times in college, two things really seem to get one by, those being joy (college romances, sporting events, sports themselves, self betterment and aggrandizement, academic success, <a href="http://www.fmylife.com" target="_blank">FML</a> and <a href="http://www.collegehumor.com" target="_blank">humor</a>) and an intermittent period of self apathy leading back to joy.</p>
<p>But as one hits the real world, life turns a little sour. Some are protected by the governing bureaucracy while others are attacked by it.  So, as a fairly ambitious grad, I&#8217;ll explore some of the issues and how I see those changing the way we live and those that should themselves be changed.</p></blockquote>
<p>As the son of two physicians, I thought I had seen medicine from every single vantage point.   I remember reading the NEJM and JAMA solely because my parents thought that cartoons and other periodicals not sent down from Wall Street or the NYTimes polluted the mind.  I was that kid at school who loved squishing worms to study the insides and then pretend that my piling the lump of guts on the asphalt was my glorified way of performing surgery.</p>
<p>But very recently I (unfortunately) was given a dose of a very unnerving side of the industry.</p>
<p>Being a strappingly healthy 22 year old hot off the books, I figured I wouldn&#8217;t need routine check ups, medicine, or any other health service for a long while, so I really wasn&#8217;t too concerned about health insurance upon graduation. I, for one, was busy trying to find employment which would hopefully provide some coverage and secondly I simply couldn&#8217;t afford the added expense an insurance premium would present on my whopping $0 income/budget/net-worth. Therein lies the dilemma.</p>
<p><strong>What exactly does someone who is unemployed, uninsured, and unprotected by the government do in this case?</strong><br />
<em>   (update:) If you can afford it, there&#8217;s something called catastrophic insurance, where you don&#8217;t get health coverage per-se, but you&#8217;re insured against ER visits and anything it leads to after, during that transitional period between jobs, schools, whatever.  As it doesn&#8217;t cover most of the costs associated with health-care (check-ups, prescriptions, etc) it has a low premium and it&#8217;s also month-to-month so you can terminate once you&#8217;re back on your feet.</em></p>
<p>With the current system as is, there is a population that fall (unrightfully so) through the gaps of the social safety net.  I hadn&#8217;t realize this as I had some friends in high school who were getting copious amounts of support from our government in the form of food stamps, loans, Medicaid, child-care support etc.  Nor did I realize how convoluted the loopholes in our social safety net were until I realized how much health care was being given to illegal immigrants to my exclusion.  I was also under the naive idea that if something were to happen to me that as a non-profit hospital, our local ER was obliged to offer me care even though I was uninsured.  Overall, I generally felt guarded by the social safety net and the governing bureaucracies  over hospitals&#8230; oh, how I was wrong.</p>
<p>I was struck with a bout of pseudo-appendicitis. Being uninsured, I tried to tough out 3 days of severe lower right quadrant pain. I had a feeling it was solely food poisoning, but as symptoms began to worsen, I didn&#8217;t want to risk my life.  It&#8217;s a crippling feeling to be in that much pain, yet being completely overtaken by the knowledge of the financial demise waiting to greet me and my treatment at the ER.</p>
<p>Once in the triage, I remember two things. The first being unnerving and unending pain, and the second, some grouchy old lady who wouldn&#8217;t stop pestering me for my signature on everything (this is where knowledge about the system might have changed my outcome, as I had no clue what I was signing and was never explained the repurcusions of failing to sign, rather, I was in such a state of desperation, I could&#8217;ve offered them my future first born to get the pain to subside).</p>
<p>Long story short, an ER consult, full body contrast CT, a follow-up consult, colonoscopy, stool sample, and a colon biopsy, it was determined that I had a bacterial infection and not appendicitis.  Oh, and $3090 ER bill (the consult was free since the surgeon was a family friend, thanks Dr. G!) and the colonoscopy was reduced to ~$1500.</p>
<p>The problem: everything, but at least I&#8217;m feeling better.  Having recovered I&#8217;ve chosen to take the time and really explore the system&#8217;s crippling nature.  Back when the election debates were in full swing, I remember the Boston Globe claiming that some 47 million Americans were without health insurance.  That&#8217;s not the figure I&#8217;m debating since not having health insurance doesn&#8217;t mean that you don&#8217;t qualify for Medicaid and even some percentage of that 47 million aren&#8217;t even documented aliens.  Rather, it&#8217;s the roughly <a href="http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052970204731804574388730954342564.html" target="_blank">5 million</a> americans [WSJ] that don&#8217;t make over $50,000/yr and don&#8217;t qualify for government programs where these issues must be corrected.  I&#8217;m not arguing that the nation caters a program to pick up the sediment fallen between the cracks, but rather, it&#8217;s that the government steps in and changes policies (both it&#8217;s very own and those of the health industry) to morph what is more or less a broken monopoly that&#8217;s sucking the resources of a nation dry into one benefiting the nation.</p>
<p>I remember visiting websites for people struck with overwhelming health care costs asking for donations in the past.  Most of the time, these are hard working individuals who were simply dealt a poor hand and left to the mercy of the public&#8217;s sympathy.  At the same time, raised in environment engulfed within the medical industry, I find it hard to believe that our leaders can watch the abuse.  I&#8217;m documenting the exploration of my (scant) options on how to get my costs covered, but with a different approach.  I am not asking for a resolution to this debt, but rather a change that affords proper and fair health care for all.  The outlook doesn&#8217;t seem so bright, since so far in, the problems our social services attempt to ameliorate seem to reward poor life choices and protect those theoretically without rights while punishing those that pay the taxes that fund the programs&#8230; interesting.</p>
<p>[Photo by <a href="http://m.flickr.com/#/photos/cornelluniversitylibrary/3856256674/">Cornell</a>]</p>
]]></content:encoded>
