			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>No one really anticipates the times in our lives that bring about unneeded stress. I found out the hard way when I recently got a speeding ticket this week.  The immediate financial stress and situational stress were such that I had no clue how to react to the officer&#8217;s questions while shuffling around trying to find my registration card.  The situation turned from bad to worse ssince I wasn&#8217;t prepared.</p>
<p>After the event, I was turning to lifehacker&#8217;s guide on how to fight a speeding ticket when I realized that my stress at the time as well as the following sour emotions could have been avoided with a little fore-thought.</p>
<p>At that moment, I decided to take all the relevant paper work (insurance card and registration) and combine them with two notecards, one for wrecks and one for speeding tickets.  The notecards are what really reduce stress as the how-to&#8217;s are written down so I don&#8217;t have to think.  For example:</p>
<p>How-to deal with a ticket:<br />
-hands at two and ten on the wheel at all times.<br />
-turn off all outside lights and turn on all interior ones<br />
-explain (politely) why you were speeding while feeding the officers ego by constantly apologizing.<br />
-when it&#8217;s your turn to talk, ask when the radar machine was last calibrated<br />
-ask to actually see the reading (it&#8217;s your right)<br />
- notes (where&#8217;s the last speeding sign, traffic around you, etc)</p>
<p>Again, the goal is to provide a pre-thought-out sense of sanity.  Some other things I can think of to do is simply making a spare key and duct taping it to an inconspicuous place on the car. What tips do you have?</p>
]]></content:encoded>
